, is the union of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and its boundary points.
 A set is compact if it is closed and bounded, and a set is precompact if
 its closure is compact.
 Consider a Lebesgue measurable and locally essentially bounded function
 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}_{\geq0}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The Filippov regularization of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left[h\right]\left(y,t\right)\triangleq\bigcap\limits _{\delta>0}\bigcap\limits _{\mu\mathbb{S}=0}\overline{\text{co}}\ h\left(\mathbb{B}_{\delta}\left(y\right)\backslash\mathbb{S},t\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{\mu\mathbb{S}=0}{\bigcap}$
\end_inset

 denotes the intersection over all sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 of Lebesgue measure zero 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Equation 2b"
key "Paden.Sastry1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, given any sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $A\leq B$
\end_inset

 is used to state 
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq b$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 The notation "a.e." (almost everywhere) means that a property 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash N$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(N\right)=0$
\end_inset

 in a measure space 
