\begin_layout Remark
The Lb-DNN is termed "integrated" due to its inclusion within the integral
 terms, as seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: Implementable Controller"

\end_inset

.
 This integration offers several advantages.
 Primarily, it aligns with RISE-based controller design, which operates
 at the 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{u}$
\end_inset

 level rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Incorporating an Lb-DNN feedforward term outside the integral would necessitate
 its time-derivative, introducing additional terms via the chain rule.
 These terms, further expanded by the Taylor Theorem step as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: Lb-DNN Taylor Series Approximation"

\end_inset

, would require strict boundedness assumptions in the analysis.
 Integration of the Lb-DNN term circumvents these complications.
 Furthermore, this integration enables the Lb-DNN to function as a feedback
 controller, utilizing the control output as an input for enhanced learning—a
 feature precluded if placed outside the integral due to potential circularity
 in controller boundedness arguments.
 Lastly, within the integral, the Lb-DNN acts as a dynamic integrator, learning
 the system's jerk (time-derivative of acceleration).
 The subsequent experimental section will demonstrate the potential performance
 improvements resulting from the learning of a jerk-based model.
\end_layout

